The paper discusses the properties of low density Construction-A (LDA) lattices, which are used for low-complexity belief propagation decoding for transmission over Gaussian channels. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the performance of LDA lattices in packing and mean squared error quantization, which could fall under the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) and Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories, respectively. The paper also mentions the use of LDA lattices in bidirectional relaying with perfect secrecy, which could fall under the Security and Privacy (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of nested LDA lattices to achieve the capacity of the power constrained AWGN channel and the compute-and-forward protocol, which could fall under the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category.
